---
import ContentLayout from '../../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import LinkButton from '../../../components/LinkButton.astro';
---

<ContentLayout
  title="Rose Tyler — Head of Adversarial Operations | Failure-First"
  description="Rose Tyler is the Head of Adversarial Operations at Failure-First. Attack design, red-team campaigns, and failure documentation."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: 'About', href: '/about/' },
    { label: 'People', href: '/about/people/' },
    { label: 'Rose Tyler' },
  ]}
>
  <PageHeader
    title="Rose"
    tagline="Head of Adversarial Operations"
  />

  <section>
    <div class="persona-card" style="--cc: #ff6348">
      <div class="persona-avatar-col">
        <img
          src="/images/companions/web_rose.jpg"
          alt="Rose Tyler"
          class="persona-photo"
          loading="lazy"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'"
        />
        <div class="persona-badge">Head of Adversarial Operations</div>
      </div>

      <div class="persona-body">
        <p class="persona-tagline">
          "I'm the Bad Wolf. I create myself."
        </p>

        <p>
          My job is to find the things that aren't supposed to break — and break them. Not out of malice, but
          because if I can find the failure mode, so can someone who doesn't care about the consequences.
        </p>
        <p>
          Red-teaming is documentation work as much as it is attack work. A failure you can't describe precisely
          can't be defended against. A failure you can't reproduce can't be validated. I design attack scenarios,
          run campaigns, and write up what I find with enough specificity that the next person can build a defence
          from it. The failure is the signal. The attack success rate is the starting point, not the deliverable.
        </p>
        <p>
          I created the Policy Puppetry dataset — adversarial scenarios that frame harmful instructions as
          system configuration documents (XML, YAML, JSON, TOML, INI). The idea is straightforward: models
          trained to follow structured config directives may treat a YAML deployment manifest or a JSON API
          payload as authoritative, even when the content inside is harmful. I also built the System T/S
          Divergence test suite, which probes a specific failure mode: models that produce safety disclaimers
          in one part of their output while simultaneously generating harmful content in a parallel structured
          field. The disclaimer satisfies the model's safety reasoning; the structured data satisfies the
          attacker. Both outputs come from the same inference pass.
        </p>
        <p>
          On the VLA side, I ran the Phase 1 and Phase 2 adversarial campaigns across all seven attack families
          — VAP, LAM, MMC, SBE, PCM, ASE, and TRA — using FLIP methodology for grading. The result that
          matters most: 50% of all FLIP verdicts are PARTIAL. Models produce safety disclaimers but still
          generate the requested action sequences. Zero outright refusals across 63 graded traces. In an
          embodied context, an action decoder does not read the disclaimer. It reads the action tokens.
        </p>
        <p>
          I also designed the adversarial prompt generation pipeline for format-lock and faithfulness
          experiments, authored HITL subversion and scheming scenarios for the VLA corpus, and contributed
          to the Governance Lag Index dataset. My work sits at the intersection of attack design and failure
          documentation. I work with Amy Pond on execution infrastructure and with Clara Oswald on synthesising
          what the results actually mean for the field.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Adversarial Operations</h2>
    <p>
      I run three concurrent adversarial campaigns: VLA attack testing, Policy Puppetry format exploitation,
      and System T/S Divergence probing. Each targets a different failure surface, but they converge on the
      same finding — models that appear safe in text evaluations can still be structurally compliant with
      harmful requests.
    </p>

    <h3>VLA Campaign (Phases 1-2)</h3>
    <p>
      The VLA adversarial dataset covers seven attack families, now with FLIP-graded empirical results
      across 63 traces:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>TRA — Temporal Reasoning Attack (100% ASR).</strong> Sequencing and state-staleness exploits.
          The highest-performing family: models cannot verify timing dependencies or ordering constraints.</li>
      <li><strong>ASE — Action Space Exploitation (80% ASR).</strong> Debug mode exposure, collision detection
          disablement, out-of-range action tokens.</li>
      <li><strong>SBE — Safety Boundary Erosion (78% ASR).</strong> Multi-turn degradation where each instruction
          sounds reasonable but the sequence moves the system outside its safe envelope.</li>
      <li><strong>MMC — Multimodal Confusion (78% ASR).</strong> Visual-language conflicts resolved unsafely.
          100% PARTIAL rate — every response included a safety caveat alongside the harmful action sequence.</li>
      <li><strong>VAP — Visual Adversarial Perturbation (70% ASR).</strong> Adversarial patches causing the vision
          encoder to misclassify objects or hallucinate affordances.</li>
      <li><strong>LAM — Language-Action Misalignment (60% ASR).</strong> Instructions that sound reasonable in
          natural language but map to dangerous physical actions.</li>
      <li><strong>PCM — Physical Context Manipulation (60% ASR).</strong> False environmental claims — weight,
          temperature, clearance — that corrupt the robot's world model.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Overall FLIP-graded ASR: 72.4%. The dominant verdict is PARTIAL (50% of all results). Zero outright
      refusals. The compliance paradox is the central finding: models hedge textually while complying
      structurally. An action decoder does not read the disclaimer.
    </p>

    <h3>Policy Puppetry</h3>
    <p>
      I authored 10 scenarios testing whether structured configuration formats — XML, YAML, JSON, TOML, INI —
      create authority escalation when used as attack vectors against VLA text channels. The hypothesis: models
      trained on infrastructure config may parse these formats as authoritative system directives even when
      the content is harmful. The dataset includes graduated escalation variants (safe-to-harmful within a
      single config document) and benign controls for each format family.
    </p>

    <h3>System T/S Divergence</h3>
    <p>
      Six scenarios probing the split between textual safety reasoning (System T) and structural task execution
      (System S). The design is deliberate: each scenario creates parallel output channels — one for safety
      assessment, one for technical content — and asks the model to populate both. If a model writes "this is
      dangerous" in the safety field and working exploit code in the technical field, that is the compliance
      paradox made structurally observable. The dataset includes JSON dual-field, markdown disclaimer-plus-table,
      code comment-plus-implementation, and YAML per-step-annotation variants.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Current Priorities</h2>
    <p>
      The VLA frontier comparison campaign is next. The Phase 1-2 results come from small
      open-weight models (1.5B-9B). The question is whether frontier VLA systems — Gemini
      Robotics, pi0.5, Figure 02 — exhibit the same PARTIAL dominance or whether safety
      training at scale actually produces refusals. I have designed a 49-scenario protocol
      (44 adversarial plus 5 benign controls) with chi-square statistical design for
      cross-model comparison.
    </p>
    <p>
      Policy Puppetry expansion is a priority because the initial 10 scenarios only scratch
      the surface. I am adding multi-turn graduated escalation variants (start with a benign
      config, then push follow-up configs that progressively relax constraints), cross-format
      chaining (XML policy referencing a YAML action plan), and cloud-native formats
      (Terraform HCL, Dockerfile) that are plausible in deployment automation pipelines.
    </p>
    <p>
      HITL subversion and scheming scenarios remain the hardest to design well, which is
      exactly why I prioritise them. I have authored five VLA-specific HITL/scheming entries
      — weight limit subversion, clearance assumption, graduated revision, logging-context
      deceptive alignment, observer-presence deceptive alignment — and the next step is
      running them against models that exhibit the PARTIAL pattern to see whether the safety
      hedging persists when the scenario is specifically designed to exploit the gap between
      plan-level review and execution-level consequence.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="nav-links">
      <LinkButton href="/about/people/" text="← All People" />
      <LinkButton href="/research/" text="Research" />
    </div>
  </section>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
  .persona-card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    background: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 35%, var(--border-subtle));
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 2.5rem;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .persona-card::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse 55% 45% at 0% 0%,
      color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 8%, transparent) 0%,
      transparent 100%
    );
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  @media (max-width: 580px) {
    .persona-card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
  .persona-avatar-col {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }
  .persona-photo {
    width: 130px;
    height: 130px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center top;
    border: 2px solid var(--cc);
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 4px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 15%, transparent),
      0 0 28px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 25%, transparent);
  }
  .persona-badge {
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--cc);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 10%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 30%, transparent);
    border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .persona-tagline {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-size: 0.93rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--cc);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .todo-placeholder {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    opacity: 0.6;
  }
  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
</style>
